04487nam a22008175i 9780823275656DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20172017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232756567 a10.1515/97808232756562doi  a(DE-B1597)554943  a(OCoLC)976434187  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPB35.P687 2017 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a4011 aPourciau, Sarah M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Writing of Spirit :bSoul, System, and the Roots of Language Science /cSarah M. Pourciau. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. “The Eternal Etymology”: From Sprachgeist to Ferdinand de Saussure -- t1. Language Ensouled -- t2. Saussure’s Dream -- t3. Verse Origins -- tPart II. Tending toward Zero: From Runes to Phonemes -- t4. Wagner’s Poetry of the Spheres -- t5. Pythagoras in the Laboratory -- t6. Jakobson’s Zeros -- tAfterword -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aContemporary thought has been profoundly shaped by the early-twentieth-century turn toward synchronic models of explanation, which analyze phenomena as they appear at a single moment, rather than diachronically as they develop through time. But the relationship between time and system remains unexplained by the standard account of this shift. Through a new history of systematic thinking across the humanities and sciences, The Writing of Spirit argues that nineteenth-century historicism wasn’t simply replaced by a more modern synchronic perspective. The structuralist revolution consisted rather in a turn toward time’s absolutely minimal conditions, and thus also toward a new theory of diachrony.Pourciau arrives at this surprising and powerful conclusion through an analysis of language-scientific theories over the course of two centuries, associated with thinkers from Jacob Grimm and Richard Wagner to the Russian Futurists, in domains as disparate as historical linguistics, phonology, acoustics, opera theory, philosophy, poetics, and psychology. The result is a novel contribution to a pressing contemporary question—namely, what role history should play in the interpretation of the present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aHistorical linguistics. 0aHistoricism. 0aLanguages, ModernxStudy and teaching. 0aLanguages, Modern--Study and teaching. 0aStructuralism (Literary analysis). 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aGerman Romanticism.  aJakobson.  aSaussure.  aSprachgeist.  aStructuralism.  ahistorical linguistics.  aphilology.  aphilosophy of history.  asystem.  awriting.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311072901640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082327565640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823275656423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823275656.jpg  a978-3-11-072901-6  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK